    <section class="page" id="welcome">
      <h2>Welcome</h2>
      <p>This zine explores the theatrical form of drollery that thrived under Puritan rule in 17th-century England. Swipe or scroll to flip through each section and discover more.</p>
    </section>
    <section class="page" id="what">
      <h2>What is a Droll?</h2>
      <p>Drolls were short, comedic sketches often adapted from longer stage plays and performed in secret. They kept English theatre alive during the Interregnum.</p>
    </section>
    <section class="page" id="glossary">
      <h2>Glossary</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Droll:</strong> A short, humorous performance piece.</li>
        <li><strong>Interregnum:</strong> The period when England was a republic (1649â€“1660).</li>
        <li><strong>Puritan:</strong> A member of a strict religious group who opposed theatre.</li>
      </ul>
    </section>
